# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 501-c-3-organization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-c-4] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] A **501(h) election** or **Conable election** is a procedure in United States tax law that allows a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization to participate in lobbying limited only by the financial expenditure on that lobbying, regardless of its overall extent.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] This allows organizations taking the 501(h) election to potentially perform a large amount of lobbying if it is done using volunteer labor or through inexpensive means.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The 501(h) election is available to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations that are not churches or private foundations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] It was introduced by Representative Barber Conable as part of the Tax Reform Act of 1976 and codified as 26 U.S.C. § 501(h), and the corresponding Internal Revenue Service (IRS) regulations were finalized in 1990.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] 501(c)(3) organizations, named after the section of the Internal Revenue Code that defines them, are U.S. nonprofit organizations with principally charitable, educational, or religious missions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] They make up 74% of all tax-exempt organizations as of 2013.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] By default, 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to a provision that "no substantial part of the activities [may be] carrying on propaganda, or otherwise attempting, to influence legislation".
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] This test, called the **substantial part test**, is subjective and not precisely defined by the IRS, potentially making it difficult for organizations engaging in policy advocacy to determine whether they are in compliance with the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] For organizations that have made the 501(h) election, this test is replaced with an **expenditure test** which is based only on the annual financial expenditure, with no other limits on the extent of their lobbying activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] An organization may take the 501(h) election by filing a one-page form with the IRS, which remains in effect until revoked by the organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The 501(h) election is not available to churches or to private foundations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Lobbying is defined as attempting to influence legislation, and is divided into two categories.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The first, direct lobbying, occurs through communication with any member or staff of Congress, or of a state or local legislature, or any government official participating in the formulation of legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The second, grassroots lobbying, is attempting to affect the opinion of the general public on legislation, although some communications to an organization's own members are excluded from this classification.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The limit on lobbying expenditure is calculated as a fraction of the organization's total tax-exempt expenditures.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] For organizations with $500,000 or less of total tax-exempt expenditures in a given year, no more than 20% of that amount may be spent on lobbying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Decreasing percentages are allowed for organizations with higher tax-exempt expenditures, with an absolute spending cap of $1,000,000 eventually being reached.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Lobbying expenses above the allowed amount are subject to a 25% excise tax, and excessive lobbying over a four-year period may lead to loss of tax-exempt status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] This cap applies to the sum of direct and grassroots lobbying expenses.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Grassroots lobbying is also subject to its own limit, which is one quarter of the total lobbying cap.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Regardless of their 501(h) status, 501(c)(3) organizations may not participate in electoral campaigns or support specific candidates for office, a prohibition that has been in effect since the passage of the Johnson Amendment in 1954.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Also, funds derived from federal government or private foundation grants or contracts may never be used for lobbying.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The expenditure caps provide a safe harbor for non-profit organizations engaging in policy advocacy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Because the limitation is expressed solely in terms of dollar amounts, organizations can effectively perform a large amount of lobbying if it is done through volunteer labor or through inexpensive media such as email or websites.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] However, the 501(h) election is not advantageous for very large non-profits whose lobbying expenditures exceed the $1,000,000 total cap or the $250,000 grassroots lobbying cap.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] These organizations may still be able to justify the expenditures as insubstantial if their operating budget is much larger, although it does entail increased risk.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Multiple commentators have called non-profit lobbying beneficial because it balances lobbying by for-profit corporations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Tufts University political science professor Jeffrey Berry wrote in *The Washington Post* that, given that many non-profits are health care or social service providers, "they are the foot soldiers in a largely private system that delivers critical services to the disadvantaged.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] They are often closer to the problems—and the solutions—than the policymakers in city halls, state capitals and Washington." In initially enacting the provision, Congress intended to increase the flow of information from non-profits to the legislative process.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Nevertheless, as of 2009, only 1.3 percent of eligible 501(c)(3) organizations had taken the 501(h) election according to one count.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] A 2003 survey of non-profits found a widespread but erroneous belief that non-profit organizations were banned from political advocacy of any sort, with little awareness of the 501(h) election.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] This was attributed to the long gap between the provision's enactment by Congress in 1976 and the publications of final rules by the IRS in 1990 and the complexity of the 501(h) provisions, as well as the IRS's lack of interest in publicizing the provision.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] A 2013 survey of executive directors of non-profit organizations in Boston found that the organizations were 6.3 times more likely to engage in policy advocacy if they had taken a 501(h) election than those who did not.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Lobbying restrictions on non-profits date to Department of the Treasury regulations in 1919.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] These regulations denied tax-exempt status to organizations that engaged in "dissemination of controversial propaganda," which included political advocacy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Commissioner*, the American Birth Control League's tax-exempt status was revoked due to its publication of a magazine supporting the repeal of birth control laws, despite its other charitable activities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The substantial part test was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1934.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] One justification given for this limitation was that donating money to influence legislation was "selfish" and not charitable if it enhanced the donors' personal interests, although the lack of a total ban on lobbying implied that non-selfish lobbying could be permitted.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] Subsequent cases important to political advocacy by non-profits include *Seasongood v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] In 1966, the Sierra Club's tax-exempt status was revoked in a high-profile case due to its publications of advertisements in *The New York Times* and *The Washington Post* opposing the construction of dams in the Grand Canyon.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The 501(h) election was enacted in the Tax Reform Act of 1976 which was introduced by Representative Barber Conable, after several attempts to introduce various similar provisions beginning in 1969.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] IRS regulations implementing the specifics of the 501(h) election were not finalized until 1990.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The public reaction to the proposed regulations lead to a congressional hearing in the House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Oversight in March 1987, followed by the establishment of an advisory board within the IRS to revise the proposed regulations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/501-h-election] The final 1990 regulations were less stringent, excluding fundraising communications from lobbying activities and establishing the four-year window for violations before tax-exempt status would be revoked.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The **Affordable Care Act** (**ACA**), formally the **Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act** (**PPACA**) and informally known as **Obamacare**, is a landmark U.S. federal statute enacted by the 111th United States Congress and signed into law by President Barack Obama on March 23, 2010.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Together with amendments made to it by the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, it represents the U.S. healthcare system's most significant regulatory overhaul and expansion of coverage since the enactment of Medicare and Medicaid in 1965.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The ACA's major provisions came into force in 2014.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2016, the uninsured share of the population had roughly halved, with estimates ranging from 20 to 24 million additional people covered.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The law also enacted delivery system reforms intended to constrain healthcare costs and improve quality.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] After it came into effect, increases in overall healthcare spending slowed, including premiums for employer-based insurance plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The increased coverage was due, roughly equally, to an expansion of Medicaid eligibility and changes to individual insurance markets.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Both received new spending, funded by a combination of new taxes and cuts to Medicare provider rates and Medicare Advantage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Several Congressional Budget Office (CBO) reports stated that overall these provisions reduced the budget deficit, that repealing ACA would increase the deficit, and that the law reduced income inequality.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The act largely retained the existing structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market, but individual markets were radically overhauled.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Insurers were made to accept all applicants without charging based on pre-existing conditions or demographic status (except age).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] To combat the resultant adverse selection, the act mandated that individuals buy insurance (or pay a monetary penalty) and that insurers cover a list of "essential health benefits".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Young people were allowed to stay on their parents' insurance plans until they were 26 years old.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Before and after its enactment the ACA faced strong political opposition, calls for repeal, and legal challenges.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Supreme Court ruled that Congress cannot use the Commerce Clause to compel individuals to buy health insurance but upheld the individual mandate by recharacterizing the penalty as a tax.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Court also held that states could opt out of the ACA's Medicaid expansion without losing existing federal Medicaid funding, while otherwise upholding the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This led Republican-controlled states to not participate in Medicaid expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Polls initially found that 43% of Americans wanted to see the law repealed or scaled back and 49% wanted to see it expanded or enacted as is.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA amended the Public Health Service Act of 1944 and inserted new provisions on affordable care into Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual insurance market was radically overhauled, and many of the law's regulations applied specifically to this market, while the structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market were largely retained.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Some regulations applied to the employer market, and the law also made delivery system changes that affected most of the health care system.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] All new individual major medical health insurance policies sold to individuals and families faced new requirements.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The requirements took effect on January 1, 2014.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual mandate required everyone to have insurance or pay a penalty.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate and limits on open enrollment were designed to avoid the insurance death spiral, minimize the free rider problem and prevent the healthcare system from succumbing to adverse selection.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate was intended to increase the size and diversity of the insured population, including more young and healthy participants to broaden the risk pool, spreading costs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, set to $0 the penalty for not complying with the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA mandated that health insurance exchanges be provided for each state.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The exchanges are regulated, largely online marketplaces, administered by either federal or state governments, where individuals, families and small businesses can purchase private insurance plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Exchanges first offered insurance for 2014.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Some exchanges also provide access to Medicaid.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] States that set up their own exchanges have some discretion on standards and prices.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] For example, states approve plans for sale, and thereby influence (through negotiations) prices.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] They can impose additional coverage requirements—such as abortion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Alternatively, states can make the federal government responsible for operating their exchanges.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Households below the federal poverty level are not eligible to receive these subsidies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Lawful Residents and some other legally present immigrants whose household income is below 100% FPL and are not otherwise eligible for Medicaid are eligible for subsidies if they meet all other eligibility requirements.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Married people must file taxes jointly to receive subsidies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Enrollees must have U.S. citizenship or proof of legal residency to obtain a subsidy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidies for an ACA plan purchased on an exchange stop at 400% of the federal poverty level (FPL).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] According to the Kaiser Foundation, this results in a sharp "discontinuity of treatment" at 400% FPL, which is sometimes called the "subsidy cliff".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] After-subsidy premiums for the second lowest cost silver plan (SCLSP) just below the cliff are 9.86% of income in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Subsidies are provided as an advanceable, refundable tax credit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The amount of subsidy is sufficient to reduce the premium for the second-lowest-cost silver plan (SCLSP) on an exchange to a sliding-scale percentage of income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The percentage is based on the percent of federal poverty level (FPL) for the household, and varies slightly from year to year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy can be used for any plan available on the exchange, but not catastrophic plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy may not exceed the premium for the purchased plan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Small businesses are eligible for a tax credit provided they enroll in the SHOP Marketplace.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] As written, ACA mandated that insurers reduce copayments and deductibles for ACA exchange enrollees earning less than 250% of the FPL.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicaid recipients were not eligible for the reductions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] So-called cost-sharing reduction (CSR) subsidies were to be paid to insurance companies to fund the reductions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] During 2017, approximately $7 billion in CSR subsidies were to be paid, versus $34 billion for premium tax credits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter was defined as mandatory spending that does not require an annual Congressional appropriation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] CSR payments were not explicitly defined as mandatory.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This led to litigation and disruption later.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The risk-corridor program was a temporary risk management device.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage reluctant insurers into ACA insurance market from 2014 to 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] For those years the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) would cover some of the losses for insurers whose plans performed worse than they expected.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Loss-making insurers would receive payments paid for in part by profit-making insurers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Similar risk corridors had been established for the Medicare prescription drug benefit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] While many insurers initially offered exchange plans, the program did not pay for itself as planned, losing up to $8.3 billion for 2014 and 2015.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Authorization had to be given so DHHS could pay insurers from "general government revenues".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2014 stated that no funds "could be used for risk-corridor payments". leaving the government in a potential breach of contract with insurers who offered qualified health plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Several insurers sued the government at the United States Court of Federal Claims to recover the funds believed owed to them under the Risk Corridors program.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] While several were summarily closed, in the case of *Moda Health v the United States*, Moda Health won a $214-million judgment in February 2017.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Wheeler stated, "the Government made a promise in the risk corridors program that it has yet to fulfill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Supreme Court reversed this ruling in the consolidated case, *Maine Community Health Options v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] United States*, reaffirming as with Judge Wheeler that the government had a responsibility to pay those funds under the ACA and the use of riders to de-obligate its from those payments was illegal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The temporary reinsurance program is meant to stabilize premiums by reducing the incentive for insurers to raise premiums due to concerns about higher-risk enrollees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was based on retrospective costs rather than prospective risk evaluations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was available from 2014 through 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Risk adjustment involves transferring funds from plans with lower-risk enrollees to plans with higher-risk enrollees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage insurers to compete based on value and efficiency rather than by attracting healthier enrollees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Of the three risk management programs, only risk adjustment was permanent.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Plans with low actuarial risk compensate plans with high actuarial risk.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA revised and expanded Medicaid eligibility starting in 2014.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] All U.S. citizens and legal residents with income up to 133% of the poverty line would qualify for coverage in any state that participated in the Medicaid program.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Previously, states could set various lower thresholds for certain groups and were not required to cover adults without dependent children.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] A 5% "income disregard" made the effective income eligibility limit for Medicaid 138% of the poverty level.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Supreme Court ruled in *NFIB v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Sebelius* that this provision of ACA was coercive, and that states could choose to continue at pre-ACA eligibility levels.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Income from self-employment and wages of single individuals in excess of $200,000 annually are subjected to an additional tax of 0.9%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The threshold amount is $250,000 for a married couple filing jointly (threshold applies to their total compensation), or $125,000 for a married person filing separately.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] In ACA's companion legislation, the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, an additional tax of 3.8% was applied to unearned income, specifically the lesser of net investment income and the amount by which adjusted gross income exceeds the above income limits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA included an excise tax of 40% ("Cadillac tax") on total employer premium spending in excess of specified dollar amounts (initially $10,200 for single coverage and $27,500 for family coverage) indexed to inflation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This tax was originally scheduled to take effect in 2018, but was delayed until 2020 by the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016 and again to 2022.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The excise tax on high-cost health plans was completely repealed as part of H.R.1865 - Further Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2020.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] An excise tax of 2.3% on medical devices and a 10% excise tax on indoor tanning services were applied as well.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The State Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) enrollment process was simplified.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Beginning September 23, 2010, dependents were permitted to remain on their parents' insurance plan until their 26th birthday, including dependents who no longer lived with their parents, are not a dependent on a parent's tax return, are no longer a student, or are married.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Businesses that employ fifty or more people but do not offer health insurance to their full-time employees are assessed additional tax if the government has subsidized a full-time employee's healthcare through tax deductions or other means.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This is commonly known as the employer mandate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This provision was included to encourage employers to continue providing insurance once the exchanges began operating.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The act includes delivery system reforms intended to constrain costs and improve quality.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] These include Medicare payment changes to discourage hospital-acquired conditions and readmissions, bundled payment initiatives, the Center for Medicare and Medicaid Innovation, the Independent Payment Advisory Board, and accountable care organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care cost/quality initiatives included incentives to reduce hospital infections, adopt electronic medical records, and to coordinate care and prioritize quality over quantity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare switched from fee-for-service to bundled payments.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] A single payment was to be paid to a hospital and a physician group for a defined episode of care (such as a hip replacement) rather than separate payments to individual service providers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Medicare Shared Savings Program (MSSP) was established by section 3022 of the Affordable Care Act.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It is the program by which an accountable care organization interacts with the federal government, and by which accountable care organizations can be created.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Act allowed the creation of accountable care organizations (ACOs), which are groups of doctors, hospitals and other providers that commit to give coordinated care to Medicare patients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACOs were allowed to continue using fee-for-service billing.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] They receive bonus payments from the government for minimizing costs while achieving quality benchmarks that emphasize prevention and mitigation of chronic disease.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Missing cost or quality benchmarks subjected them to penalties.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Unlike health maintenance organizations, ACO patients are not required to obtain all care from the ACO.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Also, unlike HMOs, ACOs must achieve quality-of-care goals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare Part D participants received a 50% discount on brand name drugs purchased after exhausting their initial coverage and before reaching the catastrophic-coverage threshold.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2020, the "doughnut hole" would be completely filled.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] From 2017 onwards, states can apply for a "waiver for state innovation" which allows them to conduct experiments that meet certain criteria.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] To obtain a waiver, a state must pass legislation setting up an alternative health system that provides insurance at least as comprehensive and as affordable as ACA, covers at least as many residents and does not increase the federal deficit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] These states can escape some of ACA's central requirements, including the individual and employer mandates and the provision of an insurance exchange.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The state would receive compensation equal to the aggregate amount of any federal subsidies and tax credits for which its residents and employers would have been eligible under ACA, if they cannot be paid under the state plan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Community Living Assistance Services and Supports Act (or CLASS Act) established a voluntary and public long-term care insurance option for employees, The program was abolished as impractical without ever having taken effect.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Consumer Operated and Oriented Plans (CO-OP), member-governed non-profit insurers, could start providing health care coverage, based on a 5-year federal loan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] As of 2017, only four of the original 23 co-ops were still in operation, including Mountain Health CO-OP.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Nutrition labeling requirements officially took effect in 2010, but implementation was delayed, and they actually took effect on May 7, 2018.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA followed a long series of unsuccessful attempts by one party or the other to pass major insurance reforms.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Innovations were limited to health savings accounts (2003), medical savings accounts (1996) or flexible spending accounts, which increased insurance options, but did not materially expand coverage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care was a major factor in multiple elections, but until 2009, neither party had the votes to overcome the other's opposition.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of an individual mandate goes back to at least 1989, when The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think-tank, proposed an individual mandate as an alternative to single-payer health care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It was championed for a time by conservative economists and Republican senators as a market-based approach to healthcare reform on the basis of individual responsibility and avoidance of free rider problems.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Specifically, because the 1986 Emergency Medical Treatment and Active Labor Act (EMTALA) requires any hospital participating in Medicare (nearly all do) to provide emergency care to anyone who needs it, the government often indirectly bore the cost of those without the ability to pay.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] President Bill Clinton proposed a major healthcare reform bill in 1993 that ultimately failed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton negotiated a compromise with the 105th Congress to instead enact the State Children's Health Insurance Program (SCHIP) in 1997.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The failed Clinton plan included a mandate for employers to provide health insurance to all employees through a regulated marketplace of health maintenance organizations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators proposed an alternative that would have required individuals, but not employers, to buy insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1993 Republican Health Equity and Access Reform Today (HEART) Act, contained a "universal coverage" requirement with a penalty for noncompliance—an individual mandate—as well as subsidies to be used in state-based 'purchasing groups'.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Advocates included prominent Republican senators such as John Chafee, Orrin Hatch, Chuck Grassley, Bob Bennett and Kit Bond.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1994 Republican Consumer Choice Health Security Act, initially contained an individual mandate with a penalty provision; however, author Don Nickles subsequently removed the mandate, stating, "government should not compel people to buy health insurance".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] At the time of these proposals, Republicans did not raise constitutional issues; Mark Pauly, who helped develop a proposal that included an individual mandate for George H.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Bush, remarked, "I don't remember that being raised at all.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2006, an insurance expansion bill was enacted at the state level in Massachusetts.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill contained both an individual mandate and an insurance exchange.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican Governor Mitt Romney used a line-item veto on some provisions, and the Democratic legislature overrode some of his changes (including the mandate).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney's implementation of the 'Health Connector' exchange and individual mandate in Massachusetts was at first lauded by Republicans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] During Romney's 2008 presidential campaign, Senator Jim DeMint praised Romney's ability to "take some good conservative ideas, like private health insurance, and apply them to the need to have everyone insured".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney said of the individual mandate: "I'm proud of what we've done.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2007 Republican Senator Bob Bennett and Democratic Senator Ron Wyden introduced the Healthy Americans Act, which featured an individual mandate and state-based, regulated insurance markets called "State Health Help Agencies".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill attracted bipartisan support, but died in committee.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Many of its sponsors and co-sponsors remained in Congress during the 2008 healthcare debate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2008 many Democrats were considering this approach as the basis for healthcare reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Experts said the legislation that eventually emerged from Congress in 2009 and 2010 bore similarities to the 2007 bill and that it took ideas from the Massachusetts reforms.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] A driving force behind Obama's healthcare reform was Peter Orszag, Director of the Office of Management and Budget.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama called Orszag his "healthcare czar" because of his knowledge of healthcare reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag had previously been director of the Congressional Budget Office, and under his leadership the agency had focused on using cost analysis to create an affordable and effective approach to health care reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag claimed that healthcare reform became Obama's top agenda item because he wanted it to be his legacy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] According to an article by Ryan Lizza in *The New Yorker*, the core of "the Obama budget is Orszag's belief [in]...a government empowered with research on the most effective medical treatments".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama bet "his presidency on Orszag's thesis of comparative effectiveness." Orszag's policies were influenced by an article in *The Annals of Internal Medicine* co-authored by Elliott S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The article presented strong evidence based on the co-authors' research that numerous procedures, therapies and tests were being delivered with scant evidence of their medical value.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] If those procedures and tests could be eliminated, this evidence suggested, medical costs might provide the savings to give healthcare to the uninsured population.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] After reading a *New Yorker* article that used the "Dartmouth findings" to compare two counties in Texas with enormous variations in Medicare costs using hard data, Obama directed that his entire staff read it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] More than anything else, the Dartmouth data intrigued Obama since it gave him an academic rationale for reshaping medicine.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of comparing the effectiveness of healthcare options based on hard data ("comparative effectiveness" and "evidence-based medicine") was pioneered by John E.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Wennberg, founder of The Dartmouth Institute, co-founder of The Foundation for Informed Medical Decision Making and senior advisor to Health Dialog Inc., a venture that he and his researchers created to help insurers implement the Dartmouth findings.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Healthcare reform was a major topic during the 2008 Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] As the race narrowed, attention focused on the plans presented by the two leading candidates, Hillary Clinton and the eventual nominee, Barack Obama.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Each candidate proposed a plan to cover the approximately 45 million Americans estimated to not have health insurance at some point each year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton's proposal would have required all Americans to obtain coverage (in effect, an individual mandate), while Obama's proposal provided a subsidy without a mandate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] During the general election, Obama said fixing healthcare would be one of his top four priorities as president.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama and his opponent, Senator John McCain, both proposed health insurance reforms, though their plans differed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] McCain proposed tax credits for health insurance purchased in the individual market, which was estimated to reduce the number of uninsured people by about 2 million by 2018.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama proposed private and public group insurance, income-based subsidies, consumer protections, and expansions of Medicaid and SCHIP, which was estimated at the time to reduce the number of uninsured people by 33.9 million by 2018 at a higher cost.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama announced to a joint session of Congress in February 2009 his intent to work with Congress to construct a plan for healthcare reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] By July, a series of bills were approved by committees within the House of Representatives.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] On the Senate side, from June to September, the Senate Finance Committee held a series of 31 meetings to develop a proposal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This group—in particular, Democrats Max Baucus, Jeff Bingaman and Kent Conrad, along with Republicans Mike Enzi, Chuck Grassley and Olympia Snowe—met for more than 60 hours, and the principles they discussed, in conjunction with the other committees, became the foundation of a Senate bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] They chose this approach after concluding that filibuster-proof support in the Senate was not present for more progressive plans such as single-payer.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] By deliberately drawing on bipartisan ideas—the same basic outline was supported by former Senate Majority Leaders Howard Baker, Bob Dole, Tom Daschle and George J.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Mitchell—the bill's drafters hoped to garner the necessary votes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] However, following the incorporation of an individual mandate into the proposal, Republicans threatened to filibuster any bill that contained it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, who led the Republican response, concluded Republicans should not support the bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators, including those who had supported earlier proposals with a similar mandate, began to describe the mandate as "unconstitutional".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] During the August 2009 summer congressional recess, many members went back to their districts and held town hall meetings on the proposals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The nascent Tea Party movement organized protests and many conservative groups and individuals attended the meetings to oppose the proposed reforms.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Threats were made against members of Congress over the course of the debate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] In September 2009 Obama delivered another speech to a joint session of Congress supporting the negotiations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] On November 7, the House of Representatives passed the Affordable Health Care for America Act on a 220–215 vote and forwarded it to the Senate for passage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate began work on its own proposals while the House was still working.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The United States Constitution requires all revenue-related bills to originate in the House.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] To formally comply with this requirement, the Senate repurposed H.R.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] 3590, a bill regarding housing tax changes for service members.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It had been passed by the House as a revenue-related modification to the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill became the Senate's vehicle for its healthcare reform proposal, discarding the bill's original content.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill ultimately incorporated elements of proposals that were reported favorably by the Senate Health and Finance committees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] With the Republican Senate minority vowing to filibuster, 60 votes would be necessary to pass the Senate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] At the start of the 111th Congress, Democrats had 58 votes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Minnesota Senate election was ultimately won by Democrat Al Franken, making 59.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Arlen Specter switched to the Democratic party in April 2009, giving them 60 seats, enough to end a filibuster.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Negotiations were undertaken attempting to satisfy moderate Democrats and to bring Republican senators aboard; particular attention was given to Republicans Bennett, Enzi, Grassley and Snowe.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] After the Finance Committee vote on October 15, negotiations turned to moderate Democrats.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid focused on satisfying centrists.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The holdouts came down to Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, an independent who caucused with Democrats, and conservative Nebraska Democrat Ben Nelson.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Lieberman's demand that the bill not include a public option was met, although supporters won various concessions, including allowing state-based public options such as Vermont's failed Green Mountain Care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter half of the compromise was derisively termed the "Cornhusker Kickback" and was later removed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] On December 23, the Senate voted 60–39 to end debate on the bill: a cloture vote to end the filibuster.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill then passed, also 60–39, on December 24, 2009, with all Democrats and two independents voting for it, and all Republicans against (except Jim Bunning, who did not vote).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill was endorsed by the American Medical Association and AARP.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] On January 19, 2010, Massachusetts Republican Scott Brown was elected to the Senate in a special election to replace the recently deceased Ted Kennedy, having campaigned on giving the Republican minority the 41st vote needed to sustain Republican filibusters.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Additionally, the symbolic importance of losing Kennedy's traditionally Democratic Massachusetts seat made many Congressional Democrats concerned about the political cost of the bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] With Democrats no longer able to get the 60 votes to break a filibuster in the Senate, White House Chief of Staff Rahm Emanuel argued that Democrats should scale back to a less ambitious bill, but House Speaker Nancy Pelosi pushed back, dismissing more moderate reform as "Kiddie Care".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama remained insistent on comprehensive reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The news that Anthem in California intended to raise premium rates for its patients by as much as 39% gave him new evidence of the need for reform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] On February 22, he laid out a "Senate-leaning" proposal to consolidate the bills.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] He held a meeting with both parties' leaders on February 25.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Democrats decided the House would pass the Senate's bill, to avoid another Senate vote.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] House Democrats had expected to be able to negotiate changes in a House–Senate conference before passing a final bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Since any bill that emerged from conference that differed from the Senate bill would have to pass the Senate over another Republican filibuster, most House Democrats agreed to pass the Senate bill on condition that it be amended by a subsequent bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] They drafted the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act, which could be passed by the reconciliation process.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Per the Congressional Budget Act of 1974, reconciliation cannot be subject to a filibuster.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] But reconciliation is limited to budget changes, which is why the procedure was not used to pass ACA in the first place; the bill had inherently non-budgetary regulations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Although the already-passed Senate bill could not have been passed by reconciliation, most of House Democrats' demands were budgetary: "these changes—higher subsidy levels, different kinds of taxes to pay for them, nixing the Nebraska Medicaid deal—mainly involve taxes and spending.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The remaining obstacle was a pivotal group of pro-life Democrats led by Bart Stupak who were initially reluctant to support the bill.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The group found the possibility of federal funding for abortion significant enough to warrant opposition.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate bill had not included language that satisfied their concerns, but they could not address abortion in the reconciliation bill as it would be non-budgetary.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Instead, Obama issued Executive Order 13535, reaffirming the principles in the Hyde Amendment to continue banning the use of federal funds for abortion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] This won the support of Stupak and members of his group and assured the bill's passage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The House passed the Senate bill with a 219–212 vote on March 21, 2010, with 34 Democrats and all 178 Republicans voting against it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] It passed the second bill, by 220–211, the same day (with the Senate passing this bill via reconciliation by 56-43 a few days later).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The day after the passage of ACA, March 22, Republicans introduced legislation to repeal it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama signed ACA into law on March 23, 2010.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] Since passage, Republicans have voted to repeal all or parts of the Affordable Care Act more than sixty times.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 eliminated the fine for violating the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] (The requirement itself is still in effect.) In 2019 Congress repealed the so-called "Cadillac" tax on health insurance benefits, an excise tax on medical devices, and the Health Insurance Tax.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] The American Rescue Plan Act of 2021, enacted during the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, expanded subsidies for marketplace health plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p01] A continuation of these subsidies was introduced as part of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The law caused a significant reduction in the number and percentage of people without health insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CDC reported that the percentage of people without health insurance fell from 16.0% in 2010 to 8.9% from January to June 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The uninsured rate dropped in every congressional district in the U.S. from 2013 to 2015.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Congressional Budget Office reported in March 2016 that approximately 12 million people were covered by the exchanges (10 million of whom received subsidies) and 11 million added to Medicaid.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Another million were covered by ACA's "Basic Health Program", for a total of 24 million.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would reduce the net number of uninsured by 22 million in 2016, using a slightly different computation for the above figures totaling ACA coverage of 26 million, less 4 million for reductions in "employment-based coverage" and "non-group and other coverage".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) estimated that 20.0 million adults (aged 18–64) gained healthcare coverage via ACA as of February 2016; similarly, the Urban Institute found in 2016 that 19.2 million non-elderly Americans gained health insurance coverage from 2010 to 2015.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2016, CBO estimated the uninsured at approximately 27 million people, or around 10% of the population or 7–8% excluding undocumented immigrants.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] States that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while those that did not had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18–64.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2016 32 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that the ACA reduced socioeconomic disparities in health care access.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Affordable Care Act reduced the percent of Americans between 18 and 64 who were uninsured from 22.3 percent in 2010 to 12.4 percent in 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] About 21 million more people have coverage ten years after the enactment of the ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Ten years after its enactment studies showed that the ACA also had a positive effect on health and caused a reduction in mortality.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes from the Affordable Care Act raised $16.3 billion in fiscal year 2015. $11.3 billion came from an excise tax placed directly on health insurers based on their market share.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Annual excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Individual mandate tax was $695 per individual or $2,085 per family at a minimum, reaching as high as 2.5% of household income (whichever was higher).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax was set to $0 beginning in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In the fiscal year 2018, the individual and employer mandates yielded $4 billion each.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes on insurers and drug makers added $18 billion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Income tax surcharges produced 437 billion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA reduced income inequality measured after taxes, due to the income tax surcharges and subsidies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that subsidies paid under the law in 2016 averaged $4,240 per person for 10 million individuals receiving them, roughly $42 billion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax subsidy for the employer market, was approximately $1,700 per person in 2016, or $266 billion total.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As of August 2016, 15 states operated their own health insurance marketplace.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Other states either used the federal exchange, or operated in partnership with or supported by the federal government.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] By 2019, 12 states and Washington DC operated their own exchanges.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2019, 37 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Those states that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while the others had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18 to 64.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Following the Supreme Court ruling in 2012, which held that states would not lose Medicaid funding if they did not expand Medicaid under ACA, several states rejected the option.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Over half the national uninsured population lived in those states.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) estimated that the cost of expansion was $6,366 per person for 2015, about 49 percent above previous estimates.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage, mostly low-income adults.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Kaiser Family Foundation estimated in October 2015 that 3.1 million additional people were not covered because of states that rejected the Medicaid expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In many states income thresholds were significantly below 133% of the poverty line.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Many states did not make Medicaid available to childless adults at any income level.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Because subsidies on exchange insurance plans were not available to those below the poverty line, such individuals had no new options.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Absent children, non-disabled adults were not eligible for Medicaid there.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies of the impact of Medicaid expansion rejections calculated that up to 6.4 million people would have too much income for Medicaid but not qualify for exchange subsidies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Several states argued that they could not afford the 10% contribution in 2020.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found that residents of Kentucky and Arkansas, which both expanded Medicaid, were more likely to receive health care services and less likely to incur emergency room costs or have trouble paying their medical bills.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Residents of Texas, which did not accept the Medicaid expansion, did not see a similar improvement during the same period.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Kentucky opted for increased managed care, while Arkansas subsidized private insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Later Arkansas and Kentucky governors proposed reducing or modifying their programs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2013 to 2015, the uninsured rate dropped from 42% to 14% in Arkansas and from 40% to 9% in Kentucky, compared with 39% to 32% in Texas.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 DHHS study found that states that expanded Medicaid had lower premiums on exchange policies, because they had fewer low-income enrollees, whose health on average is worse than that of those with higher income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In September 2019, the Census Bureau reported that states that expanded Medicaid under the ACA had considerably lower uninsured rates than states that did not.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, for adults between 100% and 399% of poverty level, the uninsured rate in 2018 was 12.7% in expansion states and 21.2% in non-expansion states.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Of the 14 states with uninsured rates of 10% or greater, 11 had not expanded Medicaid.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The drop in uninsured rates due to expanded Medicaid has broadened access to care among low-income adults, with post-ACA studies indicating an improvement in affordability, access to doctors, and usual sources of care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, issues with cost-related unmet medical needs, skipped medications, paying medical bills, and annual out-of-pocket spending have been significantly reduced among low-income adults in Medicaid expansion states compared to non-expansion states.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As well, expanded Medicaid has led to a 6.6% increase in physician visits by low-income adults, as well as increased usage of preventative care such as dental visits and cancer screenings among childless, low-income adults.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Improved health care coverage due to Medicaid expansion has been found in a variety of patient populations, such as adults with mental and substance use disorders, trauma patients, cancer patients, and people living with HIV.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Use of mental health treatment increased by 2.1 percentage points, from 43% to 45.1%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Among trauma patients nationwide, the uninsured rate has decreased by approximately 50%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Adult trauma patients in expansion states experienced a 13.7 percentage point reduction in uninsured rates compared to adult trauma patients in non-expansion states, and an accompanying 7.4 percentage point increase in discharge to rehabilitation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Following Medicaid expansion and dependent coverage expansion, young adults hospitalized for acute traumatic injury in Maryland experienced a 60% increase in rehabilitation, 25% reduction in mortality, and a 29.8% reduction in failure-to-rescue.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The study found that a cancer diagnosis in 2014 was associated with a 1.9 percentage-point absolute and 33.5% relative decrease in uninsured rates compared to a diagnosis made between 2010 and 2013.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Another study, using Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) Program data from 2010 to 2014, found that Medicaid expansion was associated with a 6.4% net increase in early stage (in situ, local, or regional) diagnoses of all cancers combined.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Expanded Medicaid coverage of PLWH has been positively associated with health outcomes such as viral suppression, retention of care, hospitalization rates, and morbidity at the time of hospitalization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) survey data found a 2.8% annual increase in viral suppression rates among all PLWH from 2010 to 2015 due to Medicaid expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As an early adopter of Medicaid expansion, Massachusetts found a 65% rate of viral suppression among all PLWH and an 85% rate among those retained in healthcare in 2014, both substantially higher than the national average.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of hospital discharge data from 2012 to 2014 in four Medicaid expansion states and two non-expansion states revealed hospitalizations of uninsured PLWH fell from 13.7% to 5.5% in the four expansion states and rose from 14.5% to 15.7% in the two non-expansion states.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, uninsured PLWH were 40% more likely to die in the hospital than insured PLWH.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Other notable health outcomes associated with Medicaid expansion include improved glucose monitoring rates for patients with diabetes, better hypertension control, and reduced rates of major post-operative morbidity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A July 2019 study by the National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) indicated that states enacting Medicaid expansion exhibited statistically significant reductions in mortality rates.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] From that study, states that took Medicaid expansion "saved the lives of at least 19,200 adults aged 55 to 64 over the four-year period from 2014 to 2017." Further, 15,600 older adults died prematurely in the states that did not enact Medicaid expansion in those years according to the NBER research.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Due to many states' failure to expand, many Democrats co-sponsored the proposed 2021 Cover Now Act that would allow county and municipal governments to fund Medicaid expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Despite the significant increase in access to insurance coverage and healthcare services across the board, the ACA's Medicaid expansion has not fully addressed problems of economic equity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics argue that Medicaid expansion has not reduced cost-sharing by a significant margin, as the amount households paid out of pocket for healthcare over the past ten years (in the form of deductibles, co-payments, etc.) rose by 77%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Additionally, 30% of providers deny Medicaid patients, which affects the accessibility of quality care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] This increase in denial may be in part because providers receive 62 cents from Medicaid for every dollar received from private insurers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies on insurance rates show that economic inequality still persists: a significantly higher proportion of those with income greater than 100% but less than 200% of the federal poverty level were uninsured from 2010 to 2015 than of those with income greater than 200% of the federal poverty level.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] This is exacerbated by the 2012 Supreme Court decision allowing states to opt out of Medicaid, since many of the states that have opted out have more vulnerable populations, with large numbers of minorities or low-income people.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Medicaid patients have also reported receiving "second-class" treatment compared to privately insured patients, with longer wait times and lower quality of care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] National health care expenditures rose faster than national income both before (2009–2013: 3.73%) and after (2014–2018: 4.82%) ACA's major provisions took effect.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium prices rose considerably before and after.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, a study published in 2016 found that the average requested 2017 premium increase among 40-year-old non-smokers was about 9 percent, although Blue Cross Blue Shield proposed increases of 40 percent in Alabama and 60 percent in Texas.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] However, some or all these costs were offset by tax credits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, the Kaiser Family Foundation reported that for the second-lowest cost "Silver plan", a 40-year old non-smoker making $30,000 per year would pay effectively the same amount in 2017 as they did in 2016 (about $208/month) after the tax credit, despite a large increase in the list price.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In other words, the subsidies increased along with the premium price, fully offsetting the increases for subsidy-eligible enrollees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium cost increases in the employer market moderated after 2009.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, healthcare premiums for those covered by employers rose by 69% from 2000 to 2005, but only 27% from 2010 to 2015, with only a 3% increase from 2015 to 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2008 to 2010 (before passage of ACA) health insurance premiums rose by an average of 10% per year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Several studies found that the 2008 financial crisis and accompanying Great Recession could not account for the entirety of the slowdown and that structural changes likely shared at least partial credit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2013 study estimated that changes to the health system had been responsible for about a quarter of the recent reduction in inflation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Paul Krawzak claimed that even if cost controls succeed in reducing the amount spent on healthcare, such efforts on their own may be insufficient to outweigh the long-term burden placed by demographic changes, particularly the growth of the population on Medicare.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A contributing factor to premium cost moderation was that the insured faced higher deductibles, copayments and out-of-pocket maximums.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In addition, many employees chose to combine a health savings account with higher deductible plans, making the net impact of ACA difficult to determine precisely.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] According to a 2014 study, ACA likely prevented an estimated 50,000 preventable patient deaths from 2010 to 2013.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Himmelstein and Woolhandler wrote in January 2017 that a rollback of ACA's Medicaid expansion alone would cause an estimated 43,956 deaths annually.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] According to the Kaiser Foundation, expanding Medicaid in the remaining states would cover up to 4.5 million persons.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2021 study found a significant decline in mortality rates in the states that opted in to the Medicaid expansion program compared with those states that did not do so.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The study reported that states decisions' not to expand Medicaid resulted in approximately 15,600 excess deaths from 2014 through 2017.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Dependent Coverage Expansion (DCE) under the ACA has had a demonstrable effect on various health metrics of young adults, a group with a historically low level of insurance coverage and utilization of care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies have also found that DCE was associated with improvements in cancer prevention, detection, and treatment among young adult patients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A study of 10,010 women aged 18–26 identified through the 2008-12 National Health Interview Survey found that the likelihood of HPV vaccination initiation and completion increased by 7.7 and 5.8 percentage points respectively when comparing before and after October 1, 2010.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A study using SEER Program data from 2007 to 2012 found a 2.7 percentage point increase in diagnosis at stage I disease for patients aged 19–25 compared with those aged 26–34 for all cancers combined.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Two 2018 *JAMA* studies found the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program (HRRP) was associated with increased post-discharge mortality for patients hospitalized for heart failure and pneumonia.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2019 *JAMA* study found that ACA decreased emergency department and hospital use by uninsured individuals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The HRRP was also shown to disproportionately penalize safety-net hospitals that predominately serve low-income patients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The study concluded that the letters, sent to 3.9 million people, may have saved 700 lives.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2020 *JAMA* study found that Medicare expansion under the ACA was associated with reduced incidence of advanced-stage breast cancer, indicating that Medicaid accessibility led to early detection of breast cancer and higher survival rates.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Recent studies have also attributed to Medicaid expansion an increase in use of smoking cessation medications, cervical cancer screening, and colonoscopy, as well as an increase in the percentage of early-stage diagnosis of all cancers and the rate of cancer surgery for low-income patients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Transition-of-care interventions and Alternative Payment Models under the ACA have also shown promise in improving health outcomes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Post-discharge provider appointment and telephone follow-up interventions have been shown to reduce 30-day readmission rates among general medical-surgical inpatients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Reductions in 60, 90, and 180 post-discharge day readmission rates due to transition-of-care interventions have also been demonstrated, and a reduction in 30-day mortality has been suggested.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The patient-centered medical home (PCMH) payment and care model, a team-based approach to population health management that risk-stratifies patients and provides focused care management and outreach to high-risk patients, has been shown to improve diabetes outcomes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The ACA overall has improved coverage and care of diabetes, with a significant portion of the 3.5 million uninsured US adults aged 18–64 with diabetes in 2009-10 likely gaining coverage and benefits such as closure of the Medicaid Part D coverage gap for insulin.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The law placed relatively little burden on households in the top quintile (top 20%) outside of the top 1%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO reported in multiple studies that ACA would reduce the deficit, and repealing it would increase the deficit, primarily because of the elimination of Medicare reimbursement cuts.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The 2011 comprehensive CBO estimate projected a net deficit reduction of more than $200 billion during the 2012–2021 period: it calculated the law would result in $604 billion in total outlays offset by $813 billion in total receipts, resulting in a $210 billion net deficit reduction.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO separately predicted that while most of the spending provisions do not begin until 2014, revenue would exceed spending in those subsequent years.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] This estimate was made prior to the Supreme Court's ruling that enabled states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion, thereby forgoing the related federal funding.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO and JCT subsequently updated the budget projection, estimating the impact of the ruling would reduce the cost estimate of the insurance coverage provisions by $84 billion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO in June 2015 forecast that repeal of ACA would increase the deficit between $137 billion and $353 billion over the 2016–2025 period, depending on the impact of macroeconomic feedback effects.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO also forecast that repeal of ACA would likely cause an increase in GDP by an average of 0.7% in the period from 2021 to 2025, mainly by boosting the supply of labor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Although the CBO generally does not provide cost estimates beyond the 10-year budget projection period because of the degree of uncertainty involved in the projection, it decided to do so in this case at the request of lawmakers, and estimated a second decade deficit reduction of $1.2 trillion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO predicted deficit reduction around a broad range of one-half percent of GDP over the 2020s while cautioning that "a wide range of changes could occur".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2017 CBO estimated that repealing the individual mandate alone would reduce the 10-year deficit by $338 billion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO cost estimates were criticized because they excluded the effects of potential legislation that would increase Medicare payments by more than $200 billion from 2010 to 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] However, the so-called "doc fix" is a separate issue that would have existed with or without ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities objected that Congress had a good record of implementing Medicare savings.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] According to their study, Congress followed through on the implementation of the vast majority of provisions enacted in the past 20 years to produce Medicare savings, although not the doc fix.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The doc fix became obsolete in 2015 when the savings provision was eliminated, permanently removing that spending restraint.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Scheiber and Cohn rejected critical assessments of the law's deficit impact, arguing that predictions were biased towards underestimating deficit reduction.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2010 David Walker said the CBO estimates were not likely to be accurate, because they were based on the assumption that the law would not change.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The employer mandate applies to employers of more than fifty where health insurance is provided only to the full-time workers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed it created a perverse incentive to hire part-timers instead.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] However, between March 2010 and 2014, the number of part-time jobs declined by 230,000 while the number of full-time jobs increased by two million.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In the public sector full-time jobs turned into part-time jobs much more than in the private sector.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found only limited evidence that ACA had increased part-time employment.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Several businesses and the state of Virginia added a 29-hour-a-week cap for their part-time employees, to reflect the 30-hour-or-more definition for full-time worker.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As of 2013, few companies had shifted their workforce towards more part-time hours (4% in a survey from the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Trends in working hours and the recovery from the Great Recession correlate with the shift from part-time to full-time work.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Other confounding impacts include that health insurance helps attract and retain employees, increases productivity and reduces absenteeism; and lowers corresponding training and administration costs from a smaller, more stable workforce.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Relatively few firms employ over 50 employees and more than 90% of them already offered insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Most policy analysts (both right and left) were critical of the employer mandate provision.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The provision generated vocal opposition from business interests and some unions who were not granted exemptions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] From the start of 2010 to November 2014, 43 hospitals in rural areas closed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed the new law had caused these closures.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Many rural hospitals were built using funds from the 1946 Hill–Burton Act.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Some of these hospitals reopened as other medical facilities, but only a small number operated emergency rooms (ER) or urgent care centers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Between January 2010 and 2015, a quarter of ER doctors said they had seen a major surge in patients, while nearly half had seen a smaller increase.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Seven in ten ER doctors claimed they lacked the resources to deal with large increases in the number of patients.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The biggest factor in the increased number of ER patients was insufficient primary care providers to handle the larger number of insured.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Monuteaux at Boston Children's Hospital analyzed national emergency department visits among children aged 0 to 17 from 2009 to 2016 using the American Community Survey (ACS) and Nationwide Emergency Department Sample (NEDS).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] They found no immediate change in pediatric emergency department visit rates the year after the ACA took full effect in 2014, but the rate of change from 2014 to 2016 was significantly higher than previous rate trends, almost 10%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Many hospitals merged and purchased physician practices, amounting to a significant consolidation of the provider industry.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] The increased market share gave them more leverage with insurers and reduced patient care options.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015 the progressive Center for Economic and Policy Research found no evidence that companies were reducing worker hours to avoid ACA requirements for employees working more than 30 hours per week.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would slightly reduce the size of the labor force and number of hours worked, as some would no longer be tethered to employers for their insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Jonathan Cohn claimed that ACA's primary employment effect was to alleviate job lock and the reform's only significant employment impact was the retirement of those who were working only to stay insured.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA updated a portion of the False Claims Act that the United States Supreme Court interpreted in *Graham County Soil & Water Conservation District v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] There, the court said that a subsection giving public officials immunity to *qui tam* lawsuits for false statements in "administrative" disclosures encompassed state officials as well as federal ones.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Because of ACA, that section specifies that the immunity is limited to federal disclosures.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Public views became increasingly negative in reaction to specific plans discussed during the legislative debate over 2009 and 2010.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Some elements were more widely favored (preexisting conditions) or opposed (individual mandate).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls found that people were concerned the law would cost more than projected and would not do enough to control costs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In a 2012 poll 44% supported the law, with 56% against.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] By 75% of Democrats, 27% of Independents and 14% of Republicans favored the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] By party affiliation, 19% of Republicans, 27% of Independents, and 59% of Democrats favored the mandate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls showed additional provisions receiving majority support, including the exchanges, pooling small businesses and the uninsured with other consumers and providing subsidies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In June 2013, a majority of the public (52–34%) indicated a desire for "Congress to implement or tinker with the law rather than repeal it".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] After the Supreme Court upheld the individual mandate, a 2012 poll held that "most Americans (56%) want to see critics of President Obama's health care law drop efforts to block it and move on to other national issues".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] As of October 2013, approximately 40% were in favor while 51% were against.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] About 29% of whites approved of the law, compared with 61% of Hispanics and 91% of African Americans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A solid majority of seniors opposed the idea and a solid majority of those under forty were in favor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2014 poll reported that 26% of Americans support ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A later 2014 poll reported that 48.9% of respondents had an unfavorable view of ACA versus 38.3% who had a favorable view (of more than 5,500 individuals).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Another held that 8% of respondents agreed the Affordable Care Act "is working well the way it is".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In late 2014, a Rasmussen poll reported Repeal: 30%, Leave as is: 13%, Improve: 52%.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015, a poll reported that 47% of Americans approved the health care law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] This was the first time a major poll indicated that more respondents approved than disapproved.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A December 2016 poll reported that: a) 30% wanted to expand what the law does; b) 26% wanted to repeal the entire law; c) 19% wanted to move forward with implementing the law as it is; and d) 17% wanted to scale back what the law does, with the remainder undecided.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Separate polls from Fox News and NBC/*WSJ*, both taken during January 2017, indicated more people viewed the law favorably than did not for the first time.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] One of the reasons for the improving popularity of the law is that Democrats who had once opposed it (many still prefer "Medicare for all") shifted their positions because ACA was under threat of repeal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] Another January 2017 poll reported that 35% of respondents believed "Obamacare" and the "Affordable Care Act" were different or did not know.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that personal experience with public health insurance programs led to greater support for the ACA, most prominently among Republicans and low-information voters.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] By the end of 2023, a Morning Consult poll of registered voters found that 57% approved of the Affordable Care Act, while 30% disapproved of it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p02] 85% of Democrats, 56% of independents, and 28% of Republicans supported the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The term "Obamacare" was originally coined by opponents as a pejorative.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] According to research by Elspeth Reeve, the expression was used in early 2007, generally by writers describing the candidate's proposal for expanding coverage for the uninsured.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The term officially emerged in March 2007 when healthcare lobbyist Jeanne Schulte Scott wrote, "We will soon see a 'Giuliani-care' and 'Obama-care' to go along with 'McCain-care', 'Edwards-care', and a totally revamped and remodeled 'Hillary-care' from the 1990s".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2007, Mitt Romney introduced it to political discourse, saying, "How can we get those people insured without raising taxes and without having government take over healthcare?' And let me tell you, if we don't do it, the Democrats will.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] If the Democrats do it, it will be socialized medicine; it'll be government-managed care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] By mid-2012, Obamacare had become the colloquial term used both by supporters and opponents.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama eventually endorsed the nickname, saying, "I have no problem with people saying Obama cares.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] I do care." By 2016 Obama explicitly and repeatedly referred to the ACA as "Obamacare".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On August 7, 2009, Sarah Palin created the term "death panels" to describe groups who would decide whether sick patients were "worthy" of medical care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] "Death panel" referred to two claims about early drafts.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] One was that under the law, seniors could be denied care due to their age and the other that the government would advise seniors to end their lives instead of receiving care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The ostensible basis of these claims was the provision for an Independent Payment Advisory Board (IPAB).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] IPAB was given the authority to recommend cost-saving changes to Medicare by facilitating the adoption of cost-effective treatments and cost-recovering measures when statutory expenditure levels were exceeded within any given three-year period.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In fact, the Board was prohibited from recommending changes that would reduce payments before 2020, and was prohibited from recommending changes in premiums, benefits, eligibility and taxes, or other changes that would result in rationing.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010, the Pew Research Center reported that 85% of Americans were familiar with the claim, and 30% believed it was true, backed by three contemporaneous polls.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The allegation was named PolitiFact's 2009 "Lie of the Year", one of FactCheck.org's "whoppers" and the most outrageous term by the American Dialect Society.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] AARP described such rumors as "rife with gross—and even cruel—distortions".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA requires members of Congress and their staffs to obtain health insurance either through an exchange or some other program approved by the law (such as Medicare), instead of using the insurance offered to federal employees (the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA explicitly denies insurance subsidies to "unauthorized (illegal) aliens".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents claimed that combining immediate coverage with no provision for preexisting conditions would lead people to wait to get insured until they got sick.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The individual mandate was designed to push people to get insured without waiting.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In the years after 2013, many insurers did leave specific marketplaces, claiming the risk pools were too small.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Five states had one insurer in 2017, 13 had two, 11 had three; the remainder had four or more.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama's previous unambiguous assurance that consumers could keep their own plans became a focal point for critics, who challenged his truthfulness.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Various bills were introduced in Congress to allow people to keep their plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] PolitiFact initially cited various estimates that only about 2% of the total insured population (4 million out of 262 million) received such notices, but readers later voted Obama's claims as the 2013 "Lie of the Year".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Opposition and efforts to repeal the legislation have drawn support from sources that include labor unions, conservative advocacy groups, Republicans, small business organizations and the Tea Party movement.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] These groups claimed the law would disrupt existing health plans, increase costs from new insurance standards, and increase the deficit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Some opposed the idea of universal healthcare.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] President Donald Trump repeatedly promised to "repeal and replace" it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2016, Mark Dayton, the governor of Minnesota, said ACA had "many good features" but it was "no longer affordable for increasing numbers of people"; he called on the state legislature to provide emergency relief to policyholders.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Dayton later said he regretted his remarks after they were seized on by Republicans seeking to repeal the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Some pointed out that the previous system also had socialist aspects.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Even for-profit private health insurance companies socialize risk and redistribute wealth from people who have it (all premium payers) to those who need it (by paying for medically necessary healthcare).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The requirement to provide emergency care also forced redistribution from people who pay insurance premiums to those who choose to be uninsured, when they visit the emergency room.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Milos Forman opined that critics "falsely equate Western European-style socialism, and its government provision of social insurance and health care, with Marxist–Leninist totalitarianism".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents challenged ACA's constitutionality in multiple lawsuits on multiple grounds.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled, 5–4, that the individual mandate was constitutional when viewed as a tax, although not under the Commerce Clause.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA withheld all Medicaid funding from states declining to participate in the expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Court ruled that this was unconstitutionally coercive and that individual states had the right to opt out without losing preexisting Medicaid funding.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Various lawsuits addressed these concerns, including *Burwell v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.*, which looked at private corporations and their duties under the ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In *Little Sisters of the Poor Saints Peter and Paul Home v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Pennsylvania*, the Supreme Court ruled 7–2 on July 8, 2020, that employers with religious or moral objections to contraceptives can exclude such coverage from an employee's insurance plan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Writing for the majority, Justice Clarence Thomas said, "No language in the statute itself even hints that Congress intended that contraception should or must be covered.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] It was Congress, not the [administration], that declined to expressly require contraceptive coverage in the ACA itself." Justices Roberts, Alito, Gorsuch, and Kavanaugh joined Thomas's opinion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Justice Elena Kagan filed a concurring opinion in the judgment, in which Stephen Breyer joined.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Biden administration planned to seek a hold on O'Connor's decision.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Supreme Court ruled, 6–3, that federal subsidies for health insurance premiums could be used in the 34 states that did not set up their own insurance exchanges.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans sued the Obama administration in 2014, alleging that cost-sharing reduction subsidy payments to insurers were unlawful because Congress had not appropriated funds to pay for them.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The argument classified the CSR subsidy as discretionary spending subject to annual appropriation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2016, a federal judge ruled for the plaintiffs, but the Obama administration appealed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Later, President Trump ended the payments.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The House sued the administration, alleging that the money for CSRs to insurers had not been appropriated, as required for any federal government spending.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA subsidy that helps customers pay premiums was not part of the suit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Without the CSRs, the government estimated that premiums would increase by 20% to 30% for silver plans.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2017, the uncertainty about whether the payments would continue caused Blue Cross Blue Shield of North Carolina to try to raise premiums by 22.9% the next year, as opposed to an increase of 8.8% that it would have sought if the payments were assured.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer ruled that the cost-sharing program was unconstitutional for spending money that has not been specifically provided by an act of Congress, but concluded that Congress had in fact authorized that program to be created.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The judge also found that Congress had provided authority to cover the spending for the tax credits to consumers who use them to help afford health coverage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer enjoined further cost-sharing payments, but stayed the order pending appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The case ended in a settlement before the Circuit Court.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Department of Justice said it would no longer defend the ACA in court, but 17 states led by California stepped in to do so.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor's decision regarding severability turned on several passages from the Congressional debate that focused on the importance of the mandate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] While he ruled the law unconstitutional, he did not overturn the law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The intervening states appealed the decision to the Fifth Circuit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] These states argued that Congress's change in the tax was only reducing the amount of the tax, and that Congress had the power to write a stronger law to this end.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor stayed his decision pending the appeal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Fifth Circuit heard the appeal on July 9, 2019; in the interim, the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Department of Justice joined with Republican states to argue that the ACA was unconstitutional, while the Democratic states were joined by the Democrat-controlled U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] An additional question was addressed, as the Republican plaintiffs challenged the Democratic states' standing to defend the ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2019, the Fifth Circuit agreed the individual mandate was unconstitutional, but did not agree that the entire law should be voided.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Instead, it remanded the case to the District Court for reconsideration of that question.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court accepted the case in March 2020, to be heard in the 2020–2021 term, with the ruling likely falling after the 2020 elections.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Democrats pointed out that the effect of invalidating the entire law would be to remove popular provisions such as the protection for preexisting conditions, and that the Republicans had still not offered any replacement plan—important issues in the 2020 elections.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 17, 2021, the Court rejected the challenge in a 7–2 decision, ruling that Texas and the other plaintiff states did not have standing to challenge the provision, leaving the full ACA intact.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In April 2024, the Biden administration issued a final rule implementing Section 1557 of the ACA, adding gender identity to Title IX's definition of discrimination based on sex.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2024, 15 states led by Tennessee sued HHS in the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] District Court for the Southern District of Mississippi, arguing that the 2024 rule violated the Administrative Procedure Act and the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2025, a federal judge struck down the 2024 rule to the extent that it prohibits discrimination against transgender people in education and health-care programs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled that promised risk corridor payments must be made even in the absence of specific appropriation of money by Congress.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Officials in Texas, Florida, Alabama, Wyoming, Arizona, Oklahoma and Missouri opposed those elements over which they had discretion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] For example, Missouri declined to expand Medicaid or establish a health insurance marketplace engaging in active non-cooperation, enacting a statute forbidding any state or local official to render any aid not specifically required by federal law.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Other Republicans discouraged efforts to advertise the law's benefits.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Some conservative political groups launched ad campaigns to discourage enrollment.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA was the subject of many unsuccessful repeal efforts by Republicans in the 111th, 112th, and 113th Congresses: Representatives Steve King and Michele Bachmann introduced bills in the House to repeal the ACA the day after it was signed, as did Senator Jim DeMint in the Senate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2011, after Republicans gained control of the House, one of the first votes held was on a bill titled "Repealing the Job-Killing Health Care Law Act" (H.R.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] All Republicans and three Democrats voted for repeal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In the Senate, the bill was offered as an amendment to an unrelated bill, but was voted down.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] President Obama said he would veto the bill had it passed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On February 3, 2015, the House of Representatives added its 67th repeal vote to the record (239 to 186).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Strong partisan disagreement in Congress prevented adjustments to the Act's provisions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] But at least one change, a proposed repeal of a tax on medical devices, received bipartisan support.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Some Congressional Republicans argued against improvements to the law on the grounds that they would weaken the arguments for repeal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Republicans attempted to defund the ACA's implementation, and in October 2013 House Republicans refused to fund the federal government unless it came with an implementation delay, after Obama unilaterally deferred the employer mandate by one year, which critics claimed he had no power to do.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The House passed three versions of a bill funding the government while submitting various versions that would repeal or delay the ACA, with the last version delaying enforcement of the individual mandate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Democratic Senate leadership said the Senate would pass only a bill without any restrictions on ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The government shutdown lasted from October 1 to October 17.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] During a midnight congressional session starting January 11, the Senate of the 115th Congress of the United States voted to approve a "budget blueprint" that would allow Republicans to repeal parts of the law "without threat of a Democratic filibuster".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The plan, which passed 51–48, was named by Senate Republicans the "Obamacare 'repeal resolution.'" Democrats opposing the resolution staged a protest during the vote.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans announced their replacement, the American Health Care Act, on March 6.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On March 24, the AHCA failed amid a revolt among Republican representatives.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On May 4 the House voted to pass the AHCA by a margin of 217 to 213.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Senate Republican leadership announced that Senate Republicans would write their own version of the bill instead of voting on the House version.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Leader McConnell named a group of 13 Republicans to draft the substitute version in private, raising bipartisan concerns about lack of transparency.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 22, Republicans released the first discussion draft, which renamed it the "Better Care Reconciliation Act of 2017" (BCRA).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 25, although no amendment proposal had garnered majority support, Republicans voted to advance the bill to the floor and begin formal consideration of amendments.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Senators Susan Collins and Lisa Murkowski were the only two dissenting Republicans, making the vote a 50–50 tie.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Vice President Mike Pence then cast the tie-breaking vote in the affirmative.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] A subsequent "Obamacare Repeal and Reconciliation Act" abandoned the "repeal and replace" approach in favor of a straight repeal, but that too failed, 45–55.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Finally, the "Health Care Freedom Act", nicknamed "skinny repeal" because it would have made the least change to ACA, failed by 49–51, with Collins, Murkowski, and McCain joining all Democrats and independents in voting against it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Donald Trump, who has historically opposed the ACA, said during the 2024 United States presidential debates that he had "concepts of a plan" to modify or scrap it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] JD Vance has said that Trump intends to allow insurance companies to discriminate against people with preexisting conditions or disability, with subsidized insurance replaced with private insurance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Kamala Harris said during her 2024 campaign that she would "maintain and grow" the ACA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] During the 2025 federal government shutdown, the ACA once again became a focal point of partisan disagreement.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On November 8–9, 2025, as the shutdown reached its 39th day, President Donald Trump urged Senate Republicans to redirect federal funds used for ACA insurance subsidies toward direct cash payments to individuals, framing the proposal as a strategy to resolve the budgetary impasse.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Several Republican senators expressed openness to the idea; Democrats rejected it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Analysts noted that the proposal lacked the bipartisan support necessary to reopen the federal government.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Contemporary reports described the dispute over the ACA's subsidy structure as one of the key issues contributing to the protracted shutdown.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Trump said he believed the law will expire once its tax credit is eliminated and not renewed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The disagreement focused on whether to continue the enhanced premium tax credits expanded under previous legislation, including the American Rescue Plan, which lowered the portion of health insurance costs consumers pay.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Observers noted that if these subsidies expired, many individuals could face significant premium increases, potentially more than doubling for some enrollees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] This raised concerns about decreased enrollment in the ACA marketplaces, especially among individuals who previously received little or no subsidy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In addition to the effects on consumers, small businesses and self-employed individuals relying on ACA marketplace plans faced potential financial strain.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Reports also highlighted that certain federal health agency employees were furloughed during the shutdown, temporarily affecting the oversight and administration of health programs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The debate over ACA funding illustrated how federal budget impasses can have immediate effects on both insurance markets and the delivery of health services.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Under both the ACA (current law) and the AHCA, the CBO reported that the health exchange marketplaces would remain stable.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] But Republican politicians took a variety of steps to undermine it, creating uncertainty that adversely impacted enrollment and insurer participation while increasing premiums.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Concern about the exchanges became another argument for reforms.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2009, former DNC chairman and former Vermont governor Howard Dean called the ACA "a bigger bailout for the insurance industry than AIG" and "an insurance company's dream".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] He viewed the bill's end form as a death of the health care reform effort.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In his 2011 book *Remedy and Reaction*, Paul Starr, the former senior advisor for Bill Clinton's health care reform plan, notes that the ACA did not make health insurance a right and did not make medical care free at the point of service.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] He criticizies the ACA on the grounds that some lower-income individuals still cannot afford treatment and go without care "if health care and insurance are treated as ordinary commodities".
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA's critics often cite its inability to control costs and lower deductibles, the difficulty for average people to compare plans, lack of a strong public option, and inadequate regulations on or alternatives (such as co-operatives) to large corporate health care companies.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010 small business tax credits took effect.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Then Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan (PCIP) took effect to offer insurance to those who had been denied coverage by private insurance companies because of a preexisting condition.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2011, insurers had stopped marketing child-only policies in 17 states, as they sought to escape this requirement.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In *National Federation of Independent Business v.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Sebelius* the Supreme Court allowed states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2013, the Internal Revenue Service ruled that the cost of covering only the individual employee would be considered in determining whether the cost of coverage exceeded 9.5% of income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Family plans would not be considered even if the cost was above the 9.5% income threshold.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 2 Obama delayed the employer mandate until 2015.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The launch for both the state and federal exchanges was beset by management and technical failings.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] HealthCare.gov, the website that offers insurance through the exchanges operated by the federal government, crashed on opening and suffered many problems.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Operations stabilized in 2014, although not all planned features were complete.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Government Accountability Office released a non-partisan study in 2014 that concluded the administration had not provided "effective planning or oversight practices" in developing the exchanges.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby* the Supreme Court exempted closely held corporations with religious convictions from the contraception rule.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] At the beginning of the 2015, 11.7 million had signed up (ex-Medicaid).
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] By the end of the year about 8.8 million consumers had stayed in the program.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] Congress repeatedly delayed the onset of the "Cadillac tax" on expensive insurance plans first until 2020 and later until 2022 and repealed it in late 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage in 2016, mostly low-income adults.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The five major national insurers expected to lose money on ACA policies in 2016, in part because the enrollees were lower income, older and sicker than expected.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] More than 9.2 million people (3.0 million new customers and 6.2 million returning) enrolled on the national exchange in 2017, down some 400,000 from 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] This decline was due primarily to the election of President Trump.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The eleven states that run their own exchanges signed up about 3 million more.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The IRS announced that it would not require that tax returns indicate a person has health insurance, reducing the effectiveness of the individual mandate, in response to Trump's executive order.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO reported in March that the healthcare exchanges were expected to be stable.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] In May the House voted to repeal the ACA using the American Health Care Act (AHCA), but the AHCA was defeated in the Senate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO estimated that the change would cause 13 million fewer people to have health insurance in 2027.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The 2017 Individual Market Stabilization Bill was proposed to fund cost-sharing reductions, provide more flexibility for state waivers, allow a new "Copper Plan" offering only catastrophic coverage, allow interstate insurance compacts, and redirect consumer fees to states for outreach.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2019, 35 states and the District of Columbia had either expanded coverage via traditional Medicaid or via an alternative program.
[src:501-c-3-organization/affordable-care-act-p03] The show aired another sketch in September 2013 with Jay Pharoah as President Obama rolling out the plan to the public, and Aaron Paul and other cast members playing ordinary Americans helping him in advocating for the legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Modern organized sports developed in the 19th century, with the United Kingdom and the United States taking the lead.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Sporting culture was especially strong in private schools and universities, and the upper and middle-class men who attended those institutions played as amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Opportunities for working classes to participate in sport were restricted by their long six-day work weeks and Sunday Sabbatarianism.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In the UK, the Factory Act 1844 gave working men half a day off, making the opportunity to take part in sport more widely available.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Working class sportsmen found it hard to play top level sport due to having to turn up for work.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] On occasion, cash prizes, particularly in individual competitions, could make up the difference; some competitors also wagered on the outcomes of their matches.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] As professional teams developed, some clubs were willing to make "broken time" payments to players, i.e., to pay top sportsmen to take time off work, and as attendances increased, paying men to concentrate on their sport full-time became feasible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Proponents of the amateur ideal deplored the influence of money and the effect it has on sports.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] It was claimed that it is in the interest of the professional to receive the highest amount of pay possible per unit of performance, not to perform to the highest standard possible where this does not bring additional benefit.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Working class sportsmen did not see why they should not be paid to play.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Hence there were competing interests between those who wished sport to be open to all and those who feared that professionalism would destroy the "Corinthian spirit", summed up as "sportsmanship, fair play, [and] playing for the love of the game".
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] This conflict played out over the course of more than one hundred years.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The "Corinthian ideal" of the gentleman amateur developed alongside muscular Christianity in late Victorian Britain, and has been analysed as a historical social phenomenon since the later 20th century.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The Corinthian Football Club founded in 1882 was the paragon of this.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] By the early 21st century the Olympic Games and all the major team sports accepted professional competitors.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, there are still some sports which maintain a distinction between amateur and professional status with separate competitive leagues.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The most prominent of these are golf and boxing.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In particular, only amateur boxers could compete at the Olympics up to 2016.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Problems can arise for amateur sportsmen when sponsors offer to help with an amateur's playing expenses in the hope of striking lucrative endorsement deals with them in case they become professionals at a later date.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] This practice, dubbed "**shamateurism**", a portmanteau of *sham* and *amateur*, was present as early as in the 19th century.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] As financial and political stakes in high-level were becoming higher, shamateurism became all the more widespread, reaching its peak in the 1970s and 1980s, when the International Olympic Committee started moving towards acceptance of professional athletes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The advent of the state-sponsored "full-time amateur athlete" of the Eastern Bloc countries further eroded the ideology of the pure amateur, as it put the self-financed amateurs of the Western countries at a disadvantage.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The Soviet Union entered teams of athletes who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] team (with their male coaches in background) posing with their trophy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] manoeuvre under the watchful eyes of her coach.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] All North American university sports are (generally) conducted by amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Even the most commercialized college sports, such as NCAA football and basketball, do not financially compensate competitors, although coaches and trainers generally are paid.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] College football coaches in Texas and other states are often the highest-paid state employees, with some drawing salaries of over five million US dollars annually.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Athletic scholarship programs, unlike academic scholarship programs, cannot cover more than the cost of food, housing, tuition, and other university-related expenses.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In order to ensure that the rules are not circumvented, stringent rules restrict gift-giving during the recruitment process as well as during and even after a collegiate athlete's career; college athletes also cannot endorse products, which some may consider a violation of free speech rights.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Some have criticized this system as exploitative; prominent university athletics programs are major commercial endeavors, and can easily rake in millions of dollars in profit during a successful season.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] College athletes spend a great deal of time "working" for the university, and earn nothing from it at the time aside from scholarships sometimes worth tens of thousands of dollars; basketball and football coaches, meanwhile, earn salaries that can compare with those of professional teams' coaches.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] They also point out that athletic scholarships allow many young men and women who would otherwise be unable to afford to go to college, or would not be accepted, to get a quality education.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Also, most sports other than football and men's basketball do not generate significant revenue for any school (and such teams are often essentially funded by football, basketball, and donations), so it may not be possible to pay athletes in all sports.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Allowing pay in some sports but not others could result in the violation of U.S. laws such as Title IX.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Through most of the 20th century the Olympics allowed only amateur athletes to participate and this amateur code was strictly enforced – Jim Thorpe was stripped of track and field medals for having taken expense money for playing baseball in 1912.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Later on, the nations of the Communist Bloc entered teams of Olympians who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Near the end of the 1960s, the Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (CAHA) felt their amateur players could no longer be competitive against the Soviet team's full-time athletes and the other constantly improving European teams.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] They pushed for the ability to use players from professional leagues but met opposition from the International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) and the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] At the IIHF Congress in 1969, the IIHF decided to allow Canada to use nine non-NHL professional hockey players at the 1970 World Championships in Montreal and Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The decision was reversed in January 1970 after IOC President Avery Brundage said that ice hockey's status as an Olympic sport would be in jeopardy if the change was made.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In response, Canada withdrew from all international ice hockey competitions and officials stated that they would not return until "open competition" was instituted.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Günther Sabetzki became president of the IIHF in 1975 and helped to resolve the dispute with the CAHA.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1976, the IIHF agreed to allow "open competition" between all players in the World Championships.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, NHL players were still not allowed to play in the Olympics, because of the unwillingness of the NHL to take a break mid-season and the IOC's amateur-only policy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Before the 1984 Winter Olympics, a dispute formed over what made a player a professional.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The IOC had adopted a rule that made any player who had signed an NHL contract but played less than ten games in the league eligible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, the United States Olympic Committee maintained that any player contracted with an NHL team was a professional and therefore not eligible to play.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The IOC held an emergency meeting that ruled NHL-contracted players were eligible, as long as they had not played in any NHL games.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] This made five players on Olympic rosters—one Austrian, two Italians and two Canadians—ineligible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Players who had played in other professional leagues – such as the World Hockey Association – were allowed to play.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Canadian hockey official Alan Eagleson stated that the rule was only applied to the NHL and that professionally contracted players in European leagues were still considered amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Murray Costello of the CAHA suggested that a Canadian withdrawal was possible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1986, the IOC voted to allow all athletes to compete in Olympic Games starting in 1988, but let the individual sport federations decide if they wanted to allow professionals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The act caused the breakup of the Amateur Athletic Union as a wholesale sports governing body at the Olympic level).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Olympic regulations regarding amateur status of athletes were eventually abandoned in the 1990s with the exception of wrestling, where the amateur fight rules are used due to the fact that professional wrestling is largely staged with pre-determined outcomes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Starting from the 2016 Summer Olympics, professionals were allowed to compete in boxing, though amateur fight rules are still used for the tournament.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] English first-class cricket distinguished between amateur and professional cricketers until 1963.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Teams below Test cricket level in England were normally, except in emergencies such as injuries, captained by amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Notwithstanding this, sometimes there were ways found to give high performing "amateurs", for example W.G.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Grace, financial and other compensation such as employment.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] On English overseas tours, some of which in the 19th century were arranged and led by professional cricketer-promoters such as James Lillywhite, Alfred Shaw and Arthur Shrewsbury, a more pragmatic approach generally prevailed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In England the division was reflected in, and for a long time reinforced by, the series of Gentlemen v Players matches between amateurs and professionals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Few cricketers changed their status, but there were some notable exceptions such as Wally Hammond who became (or was allowed to become) an amateur in 1938 so that he could captain England.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Hammond was an example of "shamateurism", in that he was offered a "job" which paid more than he earned as a professional cricketer to act as a company's representative and play cricket.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Amateurs touring abroad could claim more in expenses than professionals were paid.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Smith was a well-salaried secretary – and an amateur captain – of Warwickshire County Cricket Club.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Trevor Bailey at Essex and Reg Simpson at Nottinghamshire were in a similar situation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Professionals were often expected to address amateurs, at least to their faces, as "Mister" or "Sir" whereas the amateurs often referred to professionals by their surnames.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Newspaper reports often prefaced amateurs' names with "Mr" while professionals were referred to by surname, or sometimes surname and initials.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] At some grounds amateurs and professionals had separate dressing rooms and entered the playing arena through separate gates.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] An anecdote narrated by Fred Root epitomises the difference between amateurs and professionals: In a match against Glamorgan, the batsmen, Arnold Dyson and Eddie Bates, had collided mid-pitch, and the ball was returned to Root, the bowler.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Root did not break the stumps as both batsmen seemed injured.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] An amateur repeatedly shouted "Break the wicket, Fred, break the wicket!" until Root said: "If you want to run him out, here's the ball: you come and do it." The amateur responded with the words "Oh, I'm an amateur.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] After the Second World War the division was increasingly questioned.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] When Len Hutton was appointed as English national cricket captain in 1952 he remained a professional.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1962 the division was removed, and all cricket players became known as "cricketers".
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In Australia the amateur-professional division was rarely noticed in the years before World Series Cricket, as many top-level players expected to receive something for their efforts on the field: before World War I profit-sharing of tour proceeds was common.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Australian cricketers touring England were considered amateurs and given the title "Mr" in newspaper reports.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Before the Partition of India some professionalism developed, but talented cricketers were often employed by wealthy princely or corporate patrons and thus retained a notional amateur status.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Women's cricket has always been almost entirely amateur; however, the recent popularity of women's sport has seen many top-level female cricketers become fully professional, with top international players earning up to $300,000 before endorsements and franchise contracts.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Boot money has been a phenomenon in amateur sport for centuries.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The term "boot money" became popularised in the 1880s when it was not unusual for players to find half a crown (corresponding to 12+1⁄2 pence after decimalisation) in their boots after a game.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The Football Association prohibited paying players until 1885, and this is referred to as the "legalisation" of professionalism because it was an amendment of the "Laws of the Game".
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, a maximum salary cap of £12 per week for a player with outside employment and £15 per week for a player with no outside employment lingered until the 1960s, even as transfer fees reached over a hundred thousand pounds; again, "boot money" was seen as a way of topping up pay.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Today, the most prominent English football clubs that are not professional are semi-professional (paying part-time players more than the old maximum for top professionals).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Until 2019, when it abandoned amateur status, the most prominent true amateur men's club was probably Queen's Park, the oldest football club in Scotland, founded in 1867 and with a home ground (Hampden Park) which is one of UEFA's five-star stadia.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] They have also won the Scottish Cup more times than any club outside the Old Firm.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Amateur football in both genders is now found mainly in small village and Sunday clubs and the Amateur Football Alliance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] A peculiar situation took place in the Soviet Union which had Soviet-type economic planning in the country and no non-state enterprises were permitted.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1936 the government agency for sports adopted a decision to form competitions for "teams of [football] masters", while at the republican level there were separate competitions among teams from factories and government agencies—players were officially on the payrolls of those institutions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In this way athletes were officially getting paid as workers or officials.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Athletes of the Soviet Armed Forces Sports Society or Dynamo Sports Club (NKVD sports society) carried a rank and a uniform.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The difference between the teams of masters and other teams was that the first competed at the all-Union level and was considered non-amateur, while those at the republican level were considered to be amateur.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The preceding football competitions among cities and regions were phased away.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Around the turn of the 20th century, much of sailing was professionals paid by interested idle rich.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Today, sailing, especially dinghy sailing, is an example of a sport which is still largely populated by amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] For example, in the recent Team Racing Worlds, and the American Team Racing Nationals, most of the sailors competing in the event were amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] While many competitive sailors are employed in businesses related to sailing (including sailmaking, naval architecture, boatbuilding and coaching), most are not compensated for their own competitions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In large keelboat racing, such as the Volvo Around the World Race and the America's Cup, this amateur spirit has given way in recent years to large corporate sponsorships and paid crews.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Like other Olympic sports, figure skating used to have very strict amateur status rules.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1992, trust funds were abolished, and the International Skating Union voted both to remove most restrictions on amateurism, and to allow skaters who had previously lost their amateur status to apply for reinstatement of their eligibility.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] A number of skaters, including Brian Boitano, Katarina Witt, Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean, and Ekaterina Gordeeva and Sergei Grinkov, took advantage of the reinstatement rule to compete at the 1994 Winter Olympics.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, when all of these skaters promptly returned to the pro circuit again, the ISU decided the reinstatement policy was a failure and it was discontinued in 1995.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Prize money at ISU competitions was introduced in 1995, paid by the sale of the television rights to those events.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In addition to prize money, Olympic-eligible skaters may also earn money through appearance fees at shows and competitions, endorsements, movie and television contracts, coaching, and other "professional" activities, provided that their activities are approved by their national federations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The only activity that is strictly forbidden by the ISU is participating in unsanctioned "pro" competitions, which the ISU uses to maintain their monopoly status as the governing body in the sport.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby has provided one of the most visible and lasting examples of the tension between amateurism and professionalism during the development of nationally organised sports in Britain in the late-19th century.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby football, despite its origins in the privileged English public schools, was a popular game throughout England by around 1880, including in the large working-class areas of the industrial north.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, as the then-amateur sport became increasingly popular and competitive, attracting large paying crowds, teams in such areas found it difficult to attract and retain good players.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] This was because physically fit local men needed to both work to earn a wage – limiting the time that they could devote to unpaid sport – and to avoid injuries that might prevent them working in the future.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Certain teams faced with these circumstances wanted to pay so-called 'broken time' money to their players to compensate them for missing paid work due to their playing commitments, but this contravened the amateur policy of the Rugby Football Union (RFU).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Following a lengthy dispute on this point during the early 1890s, representatives of more than 20 prominent northern rugby clubs met in Huddersfield in August 1895 to form the Northern Rugby Football Union (NRFU), a breakaway administrative body which would permit payments to be made to players.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The NRFU initially adopted established RFU rules for the game itself, but soon introduced a number of changes, most obviously a switch from 15 to 13 players per side.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] It became the Rugby Football League in 1922, by which time the key differences in the two codes were well established, with the 13-a-side variant becoming known as rugby league.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The RFU took strong action against the clubs involved in the formation of the NRFU, all of whom were deemed to have forfeited their amateur status and therefore to have left the RFU.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] A similar interpretation was applied to all players who played either for or against such clubs, whether or not they themselves received any compensation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Such players were effectively barred *sine die* from any involvement in organised rugby union.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] These comprehensive and enduring sanctions, combined with the very localised nature of most rugby competition, meant that most northern clubs had little practical alternative but to affiliate with the NRFU in the first few years of its existence.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby football in Britain therefore became subject to a de facto schism along regional – and to some extent class – lines, reflecting the historical origins of the split.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby league – in which professionalism was permitted – was predominant in northern England, particularly in industrial areas, and was viewed as a working class game.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby union – which remained amateur – was predominant in the rest of England, as well as in Wales and Scotland.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby union also had a more affluent reputation, although there are areas – notably in South Wales and in certain English cities such as Gloucester – with a strong working-class rugby union tradition.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Discrimination against rugby league players could verge on the petty – former Welsh international Fred Perrett was once excluded in lists of players who died in the First World War due to his 'defection' to the league code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] One Member of Parliament, David Hinchliffe, described it as "one of the longest (and daftest) grievances in history" with anyone over the age of 18 associated with rugby league being banned forever from rugby union.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In Wales the position was more equivocal with clubs attempting to stem the tide of players *going north* with *boot money*, a reference to the practice of putting cash payments into player's footwear whilst they were cleaning up after a game.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Rugby union was declared "open" in August 1995 – almost exactly 100 years after the original split occurred – meaning that professionalism has been permitted in both rugby codes since that date.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, while the professional-amateur divide remained in force, there was originally very limited crossover between the two codes, the most obvious occasions being when top-class rugby union players 'switched codes' to rugby league in order to play professionally.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Welsh international Jonathan Davies was a high-profile example of this switch.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Since professionalism has been allowed in rugby union the switches have started to come the opposite way.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Union has swiftly grown to embrace the professional game with many league players joining union to take a slice of the larger amounts of money available in the sport.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Also, some rugby unions have amateur rules, most notably the Argentine Rugby Union, where all member clubs are amateur.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The Campeonato Argentino, the national championship for provincial teams, does not include players contracted to the country's Super Rugby side, the Jaguares.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Alternative sports, using the flying disc, began in the mid-sixties.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] As numbers of young people became alienated from social norms, they resisted and looked for alternative recreational activities, including that of throwing a Frisbee.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] What started with a few players, in the sixties, like Victor Malafronte, Z Weyand and Ken Westerfield experimenting with new ways of throwing and catching a Frisbee, later would become known as playing freestyle.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Organized disc sports, in the 1970s, began with promotional efforts from Wham-O and Irwin Toy (Canada), a few tournaments and professionals using Frisbee show tours to perform at universities, fairs and sporting events.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Disc sports such as freestyle, double disc court, guts, disc ultimate and disc golf became this sports first events.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Two sports, the team sport of disc ultimate and disc golf are very popular worldwide and are now being played semi professionally.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The World Flying Disc Federation, Professional Disc Golf Association, and the Freestyle Players Association, are the official rules and sanctioning organizations for flying disc sports worldwide.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Disc ultimate is a team sport played with a flying disc.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The object of the game is to score points by passing the disc to members of your own team, on a rectangular field, 120 yards (110 m) by 40 yards (37 m), until you have successfully completed a pass to a team member in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] There are currently over five million people that play some form of organized ultimate in the US.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Ultimate has started to be played semi-professionally with two newly formed leagues, the American Ultimate Disc League (AUDL) and Major League Ultimate (MLU).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The game of guts was invented by the Healy Brothers in the 1950s and developed at the International Frisbee Tournament (IFT) in Marquette, Michigan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The game of ultimate, the most widely played disc game, began in the late 1960s with Joel Silver and Jared Kass.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In the 1970s it developed as an organized sport with the creation of the Ultimate Players Association with Dan Roddick, Tom Kennedy and Irv Kalb.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Double disc court was invented and introduced in the early 1970s by Jim Palmeri.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1974, freestyle competition was created and introduced by Ken Westerfield and Discrafts Jim Kenner.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In 1976, the game of disc golf was standardized with targets called "pole holes" invented and developed by Wham-O's Ed Headrick.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Sports teams commonly exist at the high school level.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Those who participate, commonly referred to as student athletes, do so during their course of study.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In the United States, each state has one or two high school sports associations, which are members of the National Federation of State High School Associations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Over 7 million high school students participate in athletics every year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Occasionally, success in high school sports may lead to a professional career in the field.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The benefit of sports in high school is debated; some believe that they promote discipline and teamwork, while others find that they can cause injury.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] One study on the relationship between high school athletic and academic successes finds that, for the most part, higher participation and success rates in sports is positively related school-wide student successes on academic outcomes such as standardized test scores and educational attainment.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The National Center for Educational Statistics reports that student athletes have a 20% higher chance of completing a college degree, and are more likely to be employed and in better health than non-athletes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, a survey of high school athletes in 2006 showed that high school athletes are more likely to cheat inside of the classroom than non-athletes, especially boys participating in football, baseball, and basketball and girls participating in softball and basketball.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The survey does not indicate to what extent cheating contributes to the greater academic outcomes of high school athletes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In the world of middle school and high school sports, several fees have risen over the last few years making sports more expensive.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The term "Pay-to-Play" means that students and their parents must pay a flat fee to participate, and that fee often leaves out the costs of uniforms, transportation, and other team fees.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] This affects low-income families (those who earn less than $60,000 per year) and their ability to participate in the sports.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The average cost is $381 per child per sport (Pay-to-Play Sports).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Physical and mental health can improve with the right amount of physical fitness incorporated into everyday life.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] It allows for the child to have a healthy developing body, and a BMI within the normal range.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Physical activity has been proven to improve mood and decrease both stress and anxiety.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Studies have shown that the more physical activity one participates in as a child, the happier and more stable that person will be as an adult.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Thus, the more students who participate in school sports, the more students who will find themselves balanced and successful adults later in life.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In Japan, extracurricular sports activities known as bukatsudo (部活動, club activities) and high school sports are extremely popular.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In Japan, National High-school Baseball Tournament of Japan (全日本高等学校野球選手権), which highest of amateur sports of the Japan and world, that one of very interest in sports item for Japan, when held on every August, and also regional primary event held in every July on nationwide Japan.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] See also High School Baseball (ja:高校野球).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] For Japanese soccer, see High School Soccer (ja:高校サッカー).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] For Japanese high school sports in general, see Club Activities (ja:クラブ活動).
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Golf still has amateur championships, most notably the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Amateur Championship, British Amateur Championship, U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Women's Amateur, British Ladies Amateur, Walker Cup, Eisenhower Trophy, Curtis Cup and Espirito Santo Trophy.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] However, amateur golfers are far less known than players of professional golf tours such as the PGA Tour and European Tour.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Still, a few amateurs are invited to compete in open events, such as the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Open and British Open or non-open event, such as the Masters Tournament.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Amateur golfers that win open tournaments may receive a trophy but are not entitled to any prize money above £700.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In motorsports, there are various forms of amateur drivers.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] When they compete at professional events, they are often referred to as "pay drivers".
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] They have been a presence in Formula One for many years – drivers such as Felipe Nasr, Esteban Gutiérrez and Rio Haryanto bring sponsorship to the tune of $30 million for a seat, even in backmarker teams.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In sports car racing, drivers are often seeded into certain categories, including Amateur and Pro-Am classes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The vast majority of these "gentlemen drivers" however tend to participate at club level, often racing historic or classic cars, which are aimed primarily at amateurs.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] In Ireland, the Gaelic Athletic Association, or GAA, protects the amateur status of the country's national sports, including Gaelic football, hurling and camogie.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] The GAA sees Croke Park, with a capacity of 82,300 people, filled for the Senior Football and Hurling Championship finals.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Major tennis championships prohibited professionals until 1968, but the subsequent admission of professionals virtually eliminated amateurs from public visibility.
[src:501-c-3-organization/amateur-sports] Paying players was considered disreputable in baseball until 1869.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Conable was born in Warsaw, New York on November 2, 1922.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Conable was an Eagle Scout and received the Distinguished Eagle Scout Award from the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] He graduated from Cornell University in 1942, where he was president of the Quill and Dagger society and a member of the Phi Delta Theta fraternity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] He then enlisted in the Marines and was sent to the Pacific front in World War II, where he learned to speak Japanese and fought in the Battle of Iwo Jima.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] After the war, he received his law degree from Cornell University Law School in 1948, where he lived at the Cornell Branch of the Telluride Association, having been admitted to the House as a law student, after an unsuccessful attempt as an undergraduate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] He later re-enlisted and fought in the Korean War.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] In 1952, Conable married Charlotte Williams, his wife until his death.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] He died from a staphylococcus infection in 2003, at his winter home in Sarasota, Florida.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] In 1962, Conable was elected as a Republican to the New York State Senate.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] After serving one term in the New York State Senate, he was elected to the U.S.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] House of Representatives in 1964 from a Rochester-based district.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] He was known on both sides of the aisle for his honesty and integrity, at one point being voted by his colleagues the "most respected" member of Congress; he refused to accept personal contributions larger than $50.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] A long-time ally of Richard Nixon, Conable broke with him in disgust after the revelations of the Watergate scandal.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] When the White House released a tape of Nixon instructing his chief of staff H.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Haldeman to obstruct the FBI investigation, Conable said it was a "smoking gun", a phrase which quickly entered the political folklore.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] In 1980, Conable appeared in Milton Friedman's PBS documentary *Free to Choose*.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] From 1986 until August 31, 1991, Conable was president of the World Bank.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] His experience as a legislator proved crucial as he persuaded his former colleagues to almost double Congress's appropriations for the bank.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] After the Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, Conable opposed elements of the George H.W.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Bush administration and Congress which sought to take a more punitive stance toward China.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] In Conable's view, those elements were motivated by the desire to improve their position in the 1992 election by being overly harsh on China.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Conable's view was that imposing excessive punishment was ill-advised at a time when Deng Xiaoping was struggling with domestic opponents over whether to continue the reform and opening up.
[src:501-c-3-organization/barber-conable] Conable successfully encouraged the World Bank Board of Governors to take an expansive view of humanitarian loans to China, including with regard to environmental loans because of the intrinsic merit of those investments.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Certain portions of the market value of non-cash donations, such as short-term capital gains, are made non-deductible by I.R.C.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] An organization must meet certain requirements set forth in the code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Some organizations must also file a request with the Internal Revenue Service to gain status as a tax-exempt non-profit charitable organization under section 501(c)(3) of the tax code.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] There are both public and private charities.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Contributions to charitable organizations are deductible to the donor, *unless* the donee organization uses any of its net earnings to benefit a private shareholder, or if it attempts to in any way influence political campaigns or legislation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] A contribution to a charitable organization need not be fully a "gift" in the statutory sense of the word to be deductible to the donor.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The donor's allowable deduction will be reduced, however, by the amount of the "substantial benefit" conferred upon them as a result of their contribution.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] To illustrate, suppose that the American Cancer Society is hosting a formal dance as a fund-raiser (the ACS is a certified charitable organization).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Further suppose that the fair market value of a ticket to the dance is $75, and that the donor pays $375 to purchase a ticket.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The donor may claim only a $300 deduction, because the amount contributed ($375) is reduced by the amount of the benefit that he received ($75, the fair market value of the ticket).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] This holds true even if the donor does not actually attend the dance.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The taxable income of the donor is reduced by $300.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If the donor's income was in the 35% income tax bracket both before and after the deduction, the donor's tax liability (amount of taxes owed to the government) is reduced by $105.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The particular tax consequences of a donor's charitable contribution depends on the *type* of contribution that he makes.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] A taxpayer may contribute services, cash, or property to a charity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] There are a number of traps, especially that donations of short-term capital gains are generally not tax deductible.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If the donor is contributing his services to a charity, he is not entitled to a deduction for those services.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] He is however, entitled to deduct his unreimbursed expenses that he incurred in rendering them (except for child care expenses, which are considered non-deductible personal expenses).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Joy is a professional soccer player who lives in San Diego.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] She decides to volunteer her time at a non-profit (certified charity) soccer camp, located in Los Angeles for a week.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] In the ordinary course of things, Joy would charge $10,000 for these services, plus costs of transportation, board, and child care.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Assume that Joy's driving costs (gas money, oil change, etc.) amount to $150, the cost of a hotel room for the week is $400, and the cost of child care for her two kids is $500 for the week.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Joy is **not** entitled to deduct the $10,000 value of "free services" that she performed.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Nor is she entitled to deduct the $500 of child care expenses incurred in the week she was volunteering.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] However, Joy *may* deduct the $150 car expenses, as well as the $400 hotel expenses incurred in her time volunteering at the camp, for a total deduction of $550.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If the donor is contributing cash to the charity, the general rule is that there is only one limitation on the total amount that he is entitled to deduct: He may deduct his contribution only to the extent that it does not exceed 50% of his adjusted gross income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Any amount not deducted in the year he makes the contribution may be carried forward and taken the next year for up to five years.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Ordinary assets and short-term capital gain assets (*see below*) are treated like cash for purposes of the 50% cap.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] To illustrate, suppose that the donor has an adjusted gross income of $100,000.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] In the year 2004, he gives $60,000 in cash to the American Cancer Society.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Because anything over that amount is in excess of 50% of his adjusted gross income.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The remaining $10,000 (60,000 total donation minus 50,000 deducted in 2004) carries forward to 2005, at which point he may deduct it.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If the donor is contributing appreciated property, he is entitled to deduct the *value* of that property on his tax return for that year.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Neither he nor the donee organization will pay tax on the appreciation in the property.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If the property that the donor is contributing would have produced either only an ordinary gain or a short-term capital gain had he sold it, then he may deduct only his adjusted basis in the contributed property.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The taxpayer may not deduct contributions in an amount greater than 50% of his adjusted gross income (AGI) in the year of donation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Any excess may be carried forward for up to five years and may be deducted subject to the same limitations.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Abby, our taxpayer, owns a sporting goods store.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Her business is doing well so she decides to donate some of last season's inventory to The Women's Sports Foundation, a certified charitable organization.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Abby's adjusted gross income this year is $700,000.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The fair market value of Abby's donated inventory is $600,000.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Her adjusted basis in the inventory is $400,000.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] If Abby had sold the inventory, she would have recognized an ordinary gain of $200,000 (fmv of $600,000 minus adjusted basis of $400,000).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] To determine the amount that she may deduct as a charitable contribution, Abby must subtract the ordinary gain inherent in the inventory (the $200,000) from the inventory's fair market value (the $600,000).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Thus, the amount of Abby's gift is $400,000 (fmv of $600,000 minus inventory's inherent ordinary gain of $200,000).
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] But remember, since 50% of Abby's AGI is $350,000 she may deduct no more than that.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] However – assuming her AGI remains at least $100,001 and that she makes no charitable contributions at all *next year* – she may carry over the $50,000.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Charitable donations to public charities and private foundations are subject to overall caps of 50% and 30%, respectively.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Contributions over the respective AGI thresholds may be carried forward for five years, and may be deducted in subsequent years pursuant to the same restrictions.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] This restriction helps certain investors avoid giving themselves into such a low bracket that the tax value of the donation is impaired.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] A trap for the unwary U.S. investor with an asset on which there have been gains in value who contributes the asset before the gains become long-term.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The premature gift forfeits deduction of the short-term gains.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The asset can be deducted only up to the amount of its basis, and not up to the amount of its appreciated market value.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] Only an investor who holds the asset until the capital gains have become long-term is allowed to deduct the appreciated market value.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] (A) the amount of gain which would not have been long-term capital gain if the property contributed had been sold by the taxpayer at its fair market value (determined at the time of such contribution) ...
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] A further trap awaits the unwary U.S. investor who donates depreciated assets – assets on which there have been losses in value – to charity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The gift actually forfeit the tax deductibility of the capital losses, and only the depreciated (low) market value at the time of the gift is allowed to be deducted, rather than the higher basis.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] However an investor can instead sell the depreciated assets before considering a donation.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] An investor who sells can realize the resultant capital loss, which may then be deducted under the applicable capital loss rules.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] The cash proceeds after liquidating the depreciated asset may of course be donated to charity and deducted following the sale, but the tax advantages of making such donation are no better or worse than in any cash donation to charity.
[src:501-c-3-organization/charitable-contribution-deductions-in-the-united-states] In any case, such a course leaves the investor more after-tax assets to donate if so inclined.
